However, although British women with breast cancer
now have a better chance of beating the disease, the 
country still lags behind the European average.

Scientists say the death rate has fallen fastest among under 50s, claiming better treatment and not screening appears to be the reason for the decline.

They said deaths will continue falling this year to 15.95 per cent per 100,000 women compared to 18.39 per 100,000 women in 2007.

This represents a drop of 13 per cent over five years.

