Dr Rachel Greig, of the charity Breakthrough Breast Cancer, said that it was 'reassuring' to see that the number of deaths from the disease could fall at a time when the number of women contracting the disease is increasing.

She said 12,000 women a year were still dying of the disease in Britain.

Professor Carlo La Vecchia, one of
the study leaders from the University of Milan, told the Daily 
Telegraph that the figures show 'important advancements in treatment and management are playing a major role in the decline in death rates'.

A Department of Health spokesman said more than £750million was 
being invested to help diagnose cancer earlier and provide people with 
access to the latest treatments in order to save 5,000 more lives a year
by 2015.

 

